The differential gamma production cross sections at 110
and respectively 150 degrees were derived normalizing
point by point the HPGe yield to the 235U fission
chamber yield and to 235U(n,f) cross section. Only at
high neutron energy for the main transitions and on
full energy range for the less probable transitions
few channels of 8 ns time-of-flight were grouped
together from the begin of the analysis in order to
keep the relative errors due to statistics in
acceptable limits.
The following corrections were done:
- Multiplication of original data (BgNS Transactions
C91(2015)064618) to correct for fission chamber
efficiency redetermination.
- Correction for the distance between positions of the
209Bi sample and the position of the fission chamber;
- Gamma-ray detection efficiency: extended volume
source and self-attenuation of the gamma rays in the
209Bi sample. This correction was done by means of
MCNP (ver.4c2) simulations. The HPGe efficiencies
were corrected for the coincident gamma rays from
the 152Eu source (about 1%). No summing peaks of the
gamma rays with the X-rays were observed. The Al
caps of the HPGe detectors were thick enough to
absorb the X-rays;
- Angular distribution: Gauss quadrature. Integral
gamma production cross section was calculated as a
weighted sum of the differential gamma production
cross section at 150 and 110 degrees (roots of the
4th order Legendre polynomial). The contribution
of the opening of HPGe detectors to the angular
distribution was neglected;
- Multiple scattering and attenuation of neutron beam
in the Bi209 sample. Done with MCNP (ver.4c2)
simulations, except for (n,2n) cross sections;
- No acquisition dead time was observed. To avoid the
possible dead time introduced in the HPGe detectors
acquisition system by the pile-up between the
neutron induced events and the gamma-flash induced
events all the neutron bursts in which a gamma-flash
was detected were rejected in hardware. The same
bursts were rejected for the fission chamber.
The analytical expressions employed are detailed in
the above mentioned NIM paper. Together with the list
of errors on the quantities in these expressions
listed above this will allow the evaluator to
construct the covariance matrix. In this we comply
with the method recommended by F.Froehner JEFF report
18, OECD-NEA Paris (2000) and D.L.Smith, Neutron
Physics and Nuclear Data in Science and Technology,
Vol.4, OECD-NEA, Paris ISBN 0-89448-036-7 (1991).
By Arjan Plompen (2015-11-24):
We used a value of 0.984(16) as the fission chamber
efficiency, which should have been 0.861(10). The
correction factor to apply to the data is therefore
0.875(10). See p55 of EUR 25208 EN for these values.
Two large volume HPGe detectors with
closed-ended coaxial geometry. The relative
efficiency was 48.6% and respectively 75.9% at
1.332 MeV 60Co energy. The energy resolution was
2.4 keV at 1.332 MeV. The time resolution of the HPGe
detectors was around 4 ns using Slow Rise Time
Rejection function of the Constant Fraction
Discriminator. The detectors were placed backward, at
110 and 150 degrees with respect to beam direction.
The distance to the center of the 209Bi sample was
114 mm and respectively 151 mm.
The neutron flux was measured with a
multilayer 235U fission chamber placed at 197.214 m
flight path. Two HPGe detectors and the fission
chamber recorded simultaneously. The time resolution
of the time coder was 0.5 ns. Conventional
electronics was used for both HPGe detectors and
fission chamber and the Constant Fraction
Discriminators of the HPGe detectors were set up on
Slow Rise Time Rejection function. Neutron beam was
collimated before the fission chamber, its diameter
was of 6.1 cm, less than the diameter of the 235U
deposits and than the diameter of 209Bi sample. The
HPGe efficiencies were measured with a standard
point-like source of 152-Eu of 3.1E+4Bq, in the
sample position.
Total errors for the cross sections were
deduced by combining partial errors from various
sources in quadrature. Error sources considered were:
- 235U(n,f) cross section uncertainties (point
dependent) given above together the 235U(n,f) cross
sections values;
- Point-wise error (typically 10%) resulted for the
low energy transitions (around 300 keV) because of
the large corrections due to the self-absorption in
the 209Bi sample and use of the SRTR function of the
CFD. This errors include statistical counting errors,
calibration source activity error and MCNP
simulations error;
HPGe efficiencies errors were almost
the same for two detectors, ranging from 2.3% at
0.89 MeV up to 3.5% at 3 MeV gamma ray energy;

Statistical counting errors for HPGe
detectors and fission chamber are point dependent.
The statistical counting errors of the fission
chamber yield range from about 1.4% at 2MeV up to
about 3% at 18 MeV.

corresponds to 1.12 keV at 1 MeV and 35.7 keV at

Sample consisted of two disks of metallic Bi enriched
to 99.5% in 209Bi, glued together. Each disc 3 mm
thickness and 8 cm diameter. The mass of the sample
was 296.7 g.
Uranium monitor sample, vacuum evaporated deposits,
with a total areal density of 3.066(6) mg/cm2. The
isotopic composition of the U deposits was 99.826(8)%

The total inelastic cross section was constructed
based on the known 209Bi level scheme.
The contribution of the transitions which decay from
above 3.47 MeV excitation energy was neglected. Above
3.47 MeV the present values are only an lower limit
for the total inelastic cross section.
